{"url": "https://www.reddit.com/r/learnprogramming/comments/9azh01/typescript_object_filter_by_tags/", "text": "Not sure if this is the appropriate subreddit, please let me know if I should ask this somewhere else.\n\n\u200b\n\nBasically I have a bunch of objects, and within each object a property \"tags\", which is an array of tags, e.g. :  \\[\"tech\", \"health\", \"pollution\"\\].\n\n\u200b\n\nIn the UI there are three checkboxes, which are the tags themselves that the user can select and filter the feed.\n\n\u200b\n\nNow the thing I've come up with is simply check first which checkbox is true, then loop through the objects and their tag properties, and find which ones have the proper tags (which turned out to be a mess and towards hard-coding, which I don't want to use).\n\n\u200b\n\nBut I can't wrap my head around on how to make it work, if the user selects both tech & pollution, the feed will show all articles that have either tech or pollution tags, and not exclusively the articles that have both tech & pollution as tags at the same time.\n\n\u200b\n\nIs there a nice way to filter by multiple tags anyway? Any documentation I could read to understand this more? Have you ever worked on something like this with TypeScript? Any good practices for this? All these questions because I don't want to have a long and messy code for something I believe should be done with a simple and clean function. Thank you.", "score": 1, "comments": [{"body": "You should look into the functional collection methods (primarily map, filter, and reduce, but with a few others as well). They make operating on collections quite a bit easier to mentally manage. Here's an example that follows your needs:\n\n    //fake data with tags\n    const data = [\n        { tags: ['a'], name: 'Something 1' },\n        { tags: ['b'], name: 'Something 2' },\n        { tags: ['a', 'b'], name: 'Both 1' },\n        { tags: ['c'], name: 'Other 1' },\n        { tags: ['a', 'b'], name: 'Both 2' }\n    ]\n    \n    //tags you've selected, get this from your UI\n    const selectedTags = ['a', 'b'];\n    \n    //filtered collection, contains just matching items\n    const filteredData = data.filter(item => { \n        //only return true when all selected tags are present in \n        //the data item\n        return selectedTags.every(tag => {  \n            return item.tags.indexOf(tag) >= 0);\n        });\n    });", "id": "e4zal6l", "replies": [{"body": "Thank you! Will try that as soon as I get back home. But that should do it!", "id": "e4zof71", "replies": []}]}], "title": "TypeScript Object Filter by Tags"}